A content delivery network (CDN) refers to a geographically distributed group of servers which work together to provide fast delivery of Internet content.

A properly configured CDN may also help protect websites helps 
1 against some common malicious attacks, such as Distributed Denial of Service (DDOS) attacks.
2 Improving website load times

a CDN will place servers at the exchange points between different networks.

Intelligent failover provides uninterrupted service even if one or more of the CDN servers go offline due to hardware malfunction; the failover can redistribute the traffic to the other operational servers.

CDN can keep a site secured with fresh TLS/SSL certificates which will ensure a high standard of authentication, encryption, and integrity.

cuts down on origin requests and reduces bandwidth costs.